		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://scottsbasslessons.com/?page_id=1331#comment-12502</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Hi Scott,

I&#039;ve been following your video&#039;s on YouTube and have been spending quite a bit of time on your website. I studied piano when I was younger, still play, and goofed around with the bass (and other instruments) in high school. I can read music and everything but want to know the techniques and how to develop the skills, to playing bass well/smoothly. I noticed that you wore a glove and was curious about it. When I played piano I&#039;d sit far on the right of the bench and always with a boot on, play the pedal with my left leg. I have spina bifida, a neurological condition where my spinal cord was on the outside of my spine when I was born. I&#039;m about 98% paralyzed from the waist down but, for reasons no one can figure out, I CAN fire 1 of the 3 muscles in my left quads. Wearing a boot, and putting my heal, not toe, on the pedal, it hits the sustain. The boot is heavy enough to press the pedal, and with the super little movement I have, it&#039;s JUST enough to release the pedal to kill the sustain. It looks awkward the way I sit, but it works. 

I was curious about your glove and wondered if it maybe something similar. I thought maybe it was a grip-thing and sometimes squeezing, wrapping the hands, can aide in squeezing ones hand. I wasn&#039;t too far off. I think it&#039;s cool. Sometimes it doesn&#039;t matter why it works or how, it&#039;s just that it does. I&#039;ve had a lot of health issues lately. I&#039;ve wracked-up a ridiculous amount of spinal cord and brain surgeries the last 2-3 years, like WAY too many. So I&#039;ve been out of commission and at home a lot. I picked up a bass one day and figured, &quot;What the hell? Sitting here all day might as well learn something&quot;. I&#039;m shocked at the amount of free information you have shared with the world. It&#039;s inspirational that someone ISN&#039;T after every nickel they can. There is a wealth of knowledge you&#039;ve made accessible and I&#039;m taking advantage of it. Hopefully you get some good Karmic Feedback.

I just wanted to comment on the alternative medicine. I&#039;m always amazed at how many people have one little thing happen, see a specialist for &quot;X - Disease&quot; or have friend with &quot;whatever&quot;, and suddenly they are doctors. It isn&#039;t about western medicine, alternative medicine, vegan diets, anti-medication, etc. It&#039;s about learning as much as possible, hearing EVERY &quot;PROFESSIONAL&quot; opinion, doing unbiassed research and obviously, YOU making the decision. As the saying goes, &quot;you are you&#039;re best advocate&quot;.  Sometimes it takes a balance of multiple things. One of the worst things someone can do, is think they can be their own doctor. You can&#039;t replace medical school with the internet or that &#039;thing that you&#039;re friends mother did&quot;. People expect miracles with western medicine and when they don&#039;t get it, they doubt it all. I&#039;ve tried tons of different things, many didn&#039;t work or made things worse, but eventually, I found something that, along with a bunch of other things, helped. Took two years and about a dozen different medications to find what worked. 

I wish you the best of luck. Thanks so much for sharing what you have learned through the years. You&#039;re very talented!

Cheers]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Hi Scott,</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve been following your video&#8217;s on YouTube and have been spending quite a bit of time on your website. I studied piano when I was younger, still play, and goofed around with the bass (and other instruments) in high school. I can read music and everything but want to know the techniques and how to develop the skills, to playing bass well/smoothly. I noticed that you wore a glove and was curious about it. When I played piano I&#8217;d sit far on the right of the bench and always with a boot on, play the pedal with my left leg. I have spina bifida, a neurological condition where my spinal cord was on the outside of my spine when I was born. I&#8217;m about 98% paralyzed from the waist down but, for reasons no one can figure out, I CAN fire 1 of the 3 muscles in my left quads. Wearing a boot, and putting my heal, not toe, on the pedal, it hits the sustain. The boot is heavy enough to press the pedal, and with the super little movement I have, it&#8217;s JUST enough to release the pedal to kill the sustain. It looks awkward the way I sit, but it works. </p>
<p>I was curious about your glove and wondered if it maybe something similar. I thought maybe it was a grip-thing and sometimes squeezing, wrapping the hands, can aide in squeezing ones hand. I wasn&#8217;t too far off. I think it&#8217;s cool. Sometimes it doesn&#8217;t matter why it works or how, it&#8217;s just that it does. I&#8217;ve had a lot of health issues lately. I&#8217;ve wracked-up a ridiculous amount of spinal cord and brain surgeries the last 2-3 years, like WAY too many. So I&#8217;ve been out of commission and at home a lot. I picked up a bass one day and figured, &#8220;What the hell? Sitting here all day might as well learn something&#8221;. I&#8217;m shocked at the amount of free information you have shared with the world. It&#8217;s inspirational that someone ISN&#8217;T after every nickel they can. There is a wealth of knowledge you&#8217;ve made accessible and I&#8217;m taking advantage of it. Hopefully you get some good Karmic Feedback.</p>
<p>I just wanted to comment on the alternative medicine. I&#8217;m always amazed at how many people have one little thing happen, see a specialist for &#8220;X &#8211; Disease&#8221; or have friend with &#8220;whatever&#8221;, and suddenly they are doctors. It isn&#8217;t about western medicine, alternative medicine, vegan diets, anti-medication, etc. It&#8217;s about learning as much as possible, hearing EVERY &#8220;PROFESSIONAL&#8221; opinion, doing unbiassed research and obviously, YOU making the decision. As the saying goes, &#8220;you are you&#8217;re best advocate&#8221;.  Sometimes it takes a balance of multiple things. One of the worst things someone can do, is think they can be their own doctor. You can&#8217;t replace medical school with the internet or that &#8216;thing that you&#8217;re friends mother did&#8221;. People expect miracles with western medicine and when they don&#8217;t get it, they doubt it all. I&#8217;ve tried tons of different things, many didn&#8217;t work or made things worse, but eventually, I found something that, along with a bunch of other things, helped. Took two years and about a dozen different medications to find what worked. </p>
<p>I wish you the best of luck. Thanks so much for sharing what you have learned through the years. You&#8217;re very talented!</p>
<p>Cheers</p>
