		<description><![CDATA[Just discovered your series and subscribed immediately.  A few things...

- Started on drums in 1960 when I was 12.  Mom made me take guitar lessons so I&#039;d give up the drums.  Silly mom...  But it led me to guitar, bass and some keys.  
- Played in bands all over NYC &#039;til I got married in &#039;71 and moved to Joisey.  No serious playing for many years.
- Started hearing bass lines in my head in 2000.  When medication didn&#039;t help, I picked up a used bass and amp and started getting into it. Knew my way around a fretboard plus fingerpicking an acoustic guitar gave me the right hand skills.
- In 2003, my cousin Greg (keys) talked me into going to The National Guitar Workshop for a week.  Took blues bass master classes five summers in a row.
- Greg and I started a blues band in 2004...I was 56 and he was 60...we were nuts.  But we were soon 13 pieces with FIVE HORNS...and my daughter Kate was on lead vocals doing Joplin, Raitt, BB King, etc.  I also sing lead and harmony while playing bass.  Must be a leftover from my drummer days when every part of your body did something different independently.
- Now I&#039;m 65+ and play bass for a small blues band outside of Fort Worth, TX.  We practice every week and play out 2-3 times a month.  Not only do you never stop learning...you NEVER STOP PLAYING...AND GIGGING!!!!!

Also saw and read about your gloves.  I&#039;ve been diagnosed with osteoarthritis in my fingers.  Not good when you play bass and work in IT (42 years).  There are neoprene compression gloves for arthritis (Amazon).  They give me some relief on a daily basis.  Thinking of seeing if they help on a 4-hour gig.  Let you know if they are &quot;playable&quot;.

Love the lessons.  Give me plenty of new ideas.  Have been dying to learn a little slap.  Thanks for your dedication, sense of humor and giving spirit.  It is greatly appreciated.

John

PS: Check out my newest bass at www.ergoinstruments.com.  Look at the EUB4...60&quot; of solid mahogany on a chrome tripod.  A full electric fretless upright without the body.  It is a kickass &quot;stick&quot; to play!!!]]></description>
